<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-srs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Samples, populations and sampling</title>
    <p>
        In the previous chapter (<xref ref="descriptives"/>), we distinguished between <em>descriptive statistics</em> and <em>inferential statistics</em>. 
        Descriptive statistics are used to organise, summarise, and present the information contained in a dataset. 
        Inferential statistics, on the other hand, use information from a sample to draw conclusions about the wider population 
        from which the sample was selected.</p> <p>Having developed a foundation in probability, we are now ready to explore 
        <em>statistical inference</em>. Inferential statistics seeks to answer questions about populations using evidence 
        obtained from samples. Two of the fundamental objectives of statistical inference are <em>estimation</em> and 
        <em>hypothesis testing</em>. This chapter introduces the first of these concepts; <em>estimation</em>, 
        which focuses on using sample data to estimate unknown population quantities.
    </p> 
    <p>
        Before studying estimation methods, it is important to understand the principles of <em>sampling theory</em>. 
        The reliability of any estimate depends on how the sample was selected and on the natural variation that exists 
        between different samples drawn from the same population. An understanding of sampling distributions therefore 
        provides the foundation for making valid statistical inferences.
    </p> 
    <p>
        This chapter begins by introducing the key concepts of sampling and sampling distributions. 
        It then explains how sample statistics can be used to 
        estimate population parameters through point estimates and confidence intervals. Throughout the chapter, 
        these concepts are illustrated using <term>R-Instat</term>, enabling you to apply the theory by producing estimates, 
        confidence intervals, and interpreting the corresponding output using the R-Instat interface.
    </p> 

